<!-- ============================ CHAPTER 1 ============================ -->
<h1 class="pagebreak">Chapter 1 &mdash; Introduction, Intentions &amp; Goals</h1>
<p class="chapter-intro">This chapter introduces the software in plain language: why it exists, who it is for, and the full list of things it can do.</p>

<h2>1.1 What is this software?</h2>
<p>The <b>Blood Bank Management System</b> (branded &ldquo;HemoGrid&rdquo;) is an administrative web application for a
regional blood centre. It lets authorised staff manage a registry of blood donors and keep an eye on
simple operational metrics and a running activity/cash-flow ledger. It is built as two cooperating
programs: a <b>web API</b> that stores and serves data, and a <b>web UI</b> that staff use in their browser.</p>

<h2>1.2 Intentions and goals</h2>
<ul>
<li><b>Central donor registry</b> &mdash; keep every donor's details (name, age, blood group, contact, eligibility) in one searchable place.</li>
<li><b>Fast, reliable data entry</b> &mdash; add, edit and remove donor records without data getting out of sync between screen and database.</li>
<li><b>At-a-glance insight</b> &mdash; show totals, eligibility counts and a blood-group distribution chart.</li>
<li><b>Accountability</b> &mdash; record every create/update/delete in an audit ledger so actions are traceable.</li>
<li><b>Clean, maintainable code</b> &mdash; organise the project so each file has a single, clear job (the reason for the component-based backend and the components folder on the frontend).</li>
<li><b>Pleasant experience</b> &mdash; a modern interface with light/dark themes and an animated login screen.</li>
</ul>

<h2>1.3 What the system can do (features)</h2>
<table>
<tr><th>Area</th><th>Capability</th></tr>
<tr><td>Authentication</td><td>Admin login screen gates the whole workspace.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Donor Registry</td><td>List all donors, search by blood group, add, edit (&ldquo;Modify&rdquo;) and delete (&ldquo;Purge&rdquo;) donors.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Safe delete</td><td>If a donor is linked to donation records, the system clears the dependent rows first so the delete still succeeds.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Statistics</td><td>Total donors, eligible vs. deferred counts, and a blood-group distribution bar chart.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Ledger &amp; Cash Flow</td><td>An audit trail of operations with a running balance and a sparkline history.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Settings</td><td>Switch between light and dark themes.</td></tr>
</table>

<!-- ============================ CHAPTER 2 ============================ -->
<h1 class="pagebreak">Chapter 2 &mdash; System Architecture Overview</h1>
<p class="chapter-intro">This chapter shows the big picture: the two halves of the system, how they talk, and the technologies used.</p>

<p>The application is split into two independent programs that communicate over HTTP using JSON. Neither
can see the other's internals; they only agree on the shape of the data exchanged.</p>
<pre>React + Vite frontend          HTTP (JSON)          .NET Web API            SQL           MySQL
(blood-bank-ui)      ----------------------&gt;    (BloodBankAPI)      -----------&gt;      blood_bank_ms
runs on :5173        &lt;----------------------    runs on :5236       &lt;-----------      (donors, etc.)
     Axios                 CORS / JSON             Controllers + EF Core       Pomelo MySQL</pre>

<table>
<tr><th>Layer</th><th>Technology</th><th>Role</th></tr>
<tr><td>Frontend</td><td>React, Vite, Axios</td><td>The browser UI staff interact with; calls the API.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Backend</td><td>.NET (ASP.NET Core) Web API</td><td>Receives HTTP requests, applies logic, returns JSON.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Data access</td><td>Entity Framework Core (Pomelo MySQL provider)</td><td>Maps C# objects to database rows.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Database</td><td>MySQL (schema <code>blood_bank_ms</code>)</td><td>Stores the actual records.</td></tr>
</table>

<!-- ============================ CHAPTER 3 ============================ -->
<h1 class="pagebreak">Chapter 3 &mdash; Backend File Layout (Component-Based)</h1>
<p class="chapter-intro">This chapter explains how the API project is organised. The layout is component-based: responsibilities are separated into distinct folders instead of one giant controller.</p>

<p>The API follows a <b>component-based</b> organisation. Rather than putting all logic in a single
controller, the code is separated by responsibility, and the donor operations are split into four small
controllers &mdash; one per CRUD action (Create, Read, Update, Delete).</p>

<pre>BloodBankAPI/
|-- Program.cs                     App startup: database, CORS, JSON, routing
|-- appsettings.json               Configuration (MySQL connection string)
|
|-- Controllers/                   HTTP endpoints, one file per CRUD action
|   |-- DonorsReadController.cs     (R) GET  /donors, /donors/search, /donors/audit-trail
|   |-- DonorCreateController.cs    (C) POST /donors
|   |-- DonorUpdateController.cs    (U) PUT  /donors/{id}
|   |-- DonorDeleteController.cs    (D) DELETE /donors/{id}
|
|-- Dtos/                          "Data Transfer Objects": the shapes sent over the wire
|   |-- DonorFormInput.cs           what the React form sends to the API
|   |-- AuditLogEntry.cs            one line of the audit/cash-flow ledger
|
|-- Services/                      Reusable logic shared by the controllers
|   |-- AuditLedger.cs              the in-memory ledger (record + read)
|   |-- DonorMapper.cs              turns a Donor entity into the API's flat shape
|   |-- DonorWriteHelpers.cs        shared create/update logic (blood-group lookup, age)
|
|-- Models/                        EF Core entities (one class per database table)
    |-- Donor.cs, BloodGroup.cs, Donation.cs, BloodScreening.cs,
    |-- Admin.cs, AuditLog.cs, BloodInventory.cs, BloodRequest.cs,
    |-- Hospital.cs, Patient.cs
    |-- BloodBankMsContext.cs       the EF Core "DbContext" tying entities to tables</pre>

<h2>3.1 Why this structure?</h2>
<ul>
<li><b>Controllers/</b> hold only the HTTP wiring. Splitting them by CRUD keeps each file short and focused, so a person can open <code>DonorDeleteController.cs</code> and immediately understand deletion.</li>
<li><b>Dtos/</b> define the exact JSON the frontend and backend agree on, kept separate from the database entities.</li>
<li><b>Services/</b> contain logic that more than one controller needs, so it is written once and reused.</li>
<li><b>Models/</b> are the database entities generated by EF Core; they mirror the tables.</li>
</ul>
<p>All four donor controllers deliberately share the same route, <code>api/donors</code>. This works because
each one handles a different HTTP verb, so there is never a routing clash.</p>

<!-- ============================ CHAPTER 4 ============================ -->
<h1 class="pagebreak">Chapter 4 &mdash; Frontend File Layout (blood-bank-ui)</h1>
<p class="chapter-intro">This chapter details the React project's folders, especially the components directory where the UI is broken into small, single-purpose pieces.</p>

<pre>blood-bank-ui/
|-- index.html                 The single HTML page Vite serves
|-- package.json               Dependencies and scripts (npm run dev, build)
|-- vite.config.js             Vite build/dev configuration
|
|-- src/
    |-- main.jsx               Entry point: mounts &lt;App /&gt; into the page
    |-- App.jsx                The "container": owns all state + API calls
    |-- index.css / App.css    Global styles, including the light/dark theme tokens
    |
    |-- services/
    |   |-- api.js             The single Axios client every request goes through
    |
    |-- components/            The UI broken into small, reusable pieces
        |-- LoginScreen.jsx    The logged-out sign-in view
        |-- WaveCanvas.jsx     The animated background used on the login screen
        |-- Sidebar.jsx        Left navigation rail + logout
        |-- TopHeader.jsx      Title bar + "Onboard New Donor" button
        |-- DonorsTab.jsx      Search bar + donor results table
        |-- StatsTab.jsx       Summary cards + distribution chart
        |-- LedgerTab.jsx      Balance card + sparkline + audit table
        |-- SettingsTab.jsx    Light/dark theme switch
        |-- DonorModal.jsx     Add/edit donor dialog
        |-- Footer.jsx         Address/copyright footer</pre>

<h2>4.1 How the pieces relate</h2>
<p><code>App.jsx</code> is the brain: it holds all the state (the donor list, the form, the theme, etc.) and all
the functions that call the API. Everything inside <code>components/</code> is &ldquo;presentational&rdquo; &mdash; each component
receives data and callback functions from <code>App.jsx</code> as <i>props</i> and simply renders them. This keeps the
logic in one place and the visuals cleanly separated.</p>

<!-- ============================ CHAPTER 5 ============================ -->
<h1 class="pagebreak">Chapter 5 &mdash; Backend Code Walkthrough</h1>
<p class="chapter-intro">This chapter presents every backend file with its full source and a plain-English explanation of what it does.</p>

<h2>5.1 Program.cs &mdash; application startup</h2>
<p>This file runs once when the API starts. It reads the MySQL connection string, registers the database
context, opens CORS for the local frontend, configures JSON, and maps the controllers. The order matters:
<code>UseCors</code> must run before <code>MapControllers</code>.</p>
<pre>using Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore;

var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

var connectionString = builder.Configuration.GetConnectionString("DefaultConnection");

// Explicit version instead of ServerVersion.AutoDetect, which connects at startup and would
// take the whole API down if MySQL happens to be unavailable. Change this if your server differs.
var serverVersion = new MySqlServerVersion(new Version(8, 0, 0));

builder.Services.AddDbContext&lt;BloodBankAPI.Models.BloodBankMsContext&gt;(options =&gt;
    options.UseMySql(connectionString, serverVersion));

// Allow any localhost origin in development, since Vite's port isn't always 5173.
builder.Services.AddCors(options =&gt;
{
    options.AddPolicy("AllowReactApp",
        policy =&gt; policy
            .SetIsOriginAllowed(origin =&gt;
            {
                if (string.IsNullOrEmpty(origin)) return false;
                if (!Uri.TryCreate(origin, UriKind.Absolute, out var uri)) return false;
                return uri.Host == "localhost" || uri.Host == "127.0.0.1";
            })
            .AllowAnyMethod()
            .AllowAnyHeader());
});

builder.Services.AddControllers().AddJsonOptions(options =&gt;
{
    options.JsonSerializerOptions.ReferenceHandler = System.Text.Json.Serialization.ReferenceHandler.IgnoreCycles;
});
builder.Services.AddOpenApi();

var app = builder.Build();

// UseCors must run before MapControllers.
app.UseCors("AllowReactApp");

if (app.Environment.IsDevelopment())
{
    app.MapOpenApi();
}

app.MapControllers();

app.Run();</pre>

